{"title_page": "Typhoon Treasure", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Typhoon Treasure\n|image          =\n|caption        =\n|director       = [[Noel Monkman]]\n|producer       = [[Noel Monkman]]\n|writer         = [[John P. McLeod]]\n|based on       = story by Noel Monkman\n|starring       = [[Campbell Copelin]]<br>[[Gwen Munro]]<br>[[Joe Valli]]\n|music          =\n|cinematography = George Malcolm<br>Harry Malcolm<br>Bruce A. Cummings (underwater)\n|editing        =\n|studio         = Commonwealth Film Laboratories \n|distributor    = [[United Artists]] (Aust)\n|released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1938|09| |Australia|1943| | |UK}}\n|runtime        = 89 minutes\n|country        = Australia\n|language       = English\n|budget         =\n}}\n'''''Typhoon Treasure''''' is a 1938 Australian adventure film directed by [[Noel Monkman]] and starring [[Campbell Copelin]], [[Gwen Munro]], and [[Joe Valli]]. It is set in [[New Guinea]] although shot on the [[Great Barrier Reef]] and the [[Queensland]] coast. It was Monkman's first dramatic feature film after several years making documentaries.\n\n==Premise==\nAlan Richards is the sole survivor of a [[pearling lugger]] which has been shipwrecked on [[Pakema Reef]] during a typhoon. He sets out to recover some pearls which went missing in the wreck, crossing through the jungle and fighting headhunters.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Campbell Copelin]] as Alan Richards\n*[[Gwen Munro]] as Jean Roberts\n*[[Joe Valli]] as Scotty McLeod\n*Douglas Herald as Buck Thompson\n*[[Kenneth Brampton]] as Alfred Webb\n*Norman French as patrol officer\n*Utan Walters as Utan\n*[[Marshall Crosby]]\n*Moncrieff Macallum\n*Ossie Wenban\n*Douglas Channell\n*Benjamin Brown\n\n==Production==\nIn the mid 1930s, Noel Monkman was working with [[F. W. Thring]] making documentaries. Thring offered to back Monkman in making a dramatic feature, and provided him with a writer, [[John P. McLeod]]. Thring planned to make the movie after visiting Hollywood in 1936<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11037845 |title=Entertainments GOOD VAUDEVILLE. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=28 May 1936 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> but died that year.\n\n[[Cinesound Productions]] offered to buy the script but Monkman elected to make it himself. He formed a syndicate with Bruce Cummings and Commonwealth Laboratories, who provided the crew.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27987813 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILM. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 May 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41809965 |title=\"TYPHOON TREASURE.\". |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=25 June 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFilming commenced June 1937. The film was shot mostly on location in North Queensland, on the [[Great Barrier Reef]], the Yorke Peninsula and [[Torres Strait]]. [[Joe Valli]] started filming in June but [[Gwen Munro]] did not arrive until October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41820134 |title=TALKIE STAR ARRIVES. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=6 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41817632 |title=JOE VALLI IS BACK. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=26 June 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter the location work was completed, some studio scenes were filmed at Commonwealth Film Laboratories' studio at the [[Sydney Showground (Moore Park)|Sydney Showground]].<ref name=\"pike\"/>\n\nMusic was collated from popular classics including [[Tchaikovsky]]'s ''Swan Lake''.\n\n===Death of crew member===\nWhile filming underwater scenes on [[Green Island (Queensland)|Green Island]] in October, one of the divers, James Bell, died of [[myocarditis]]. Bruce Cummings, who was in charge of underwater photography, went down in a diving cylinder, followed a few minutes later by Bell, who was his assistant. A few minutes later Cummings noticed something was wrong with Bell. When they brought him to the surface he was dead.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36383001 |title=DIVER DEAD WHEN BROUGHT UP. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=29 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=30 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41823852 |title=DEATH OF DIVER. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=28 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> An inquest was later held which found no negligence.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41833452 |title=DIVER'S COLLAPSE. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=24 December 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41835171 |title=Death of Film Diver. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=5 January 1938 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nReviews generally found the story formulaic but enjoyed the direction and settings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17533043 |title=FILM REVIEWS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=31 October 1938 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIt was sold to America<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17614362 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILM FOR AMERICAN RELEASE. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=15 June 1939 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and a shortened version of the film screened in England in 1943. In the 1950s rights to the film were bought by George Maclolm who cut it down to 40 minutes and reissued it as ''The Perils of Pakema Reef''.<ref name=\"pike\">Andrew Pike and Ross Cooper, Australian Film 1900\u20131977: A Guide to Feature Film Production, Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1998, 182.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0032069|title=Typhoon Treasure}}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=typhoon%20treasure;querytype=;rec=3;resCount=10 ''Typhoon Treasure''] at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n*[http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/typhoon-treasure ''Typhoon Treasure''] at Oz Movies\n\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure films]]\n[[Category:Australian adventure films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Typhoon Treasure\n|image          =\n|caption        =\n|director       = [[Noel Monkman]]\n|producer       = [[Noel Monkman]]\n|writer         = [[John P. McLeod]]\n|based on       = story by Noel Monkman\n|starring       = [[Campbell Copelin]]<br>[[Gwen Munro]]<br>[[Joe Valli]]\n|music          =\n|cinematography = George Malcolm<br>Harry Malcolm<br>Bruce A. Cummings (underwater)\n|editing        =\n|studio         = Commonwealth Film Laboratories \n|distributor    = [[United Artists]] (Aust)\n|released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1938|09| |Australia|1943| | |UK}}\n|runtime        = 89 minutes\n|country        = Australia\n|language       = English\n|budget         =\n}}\n'''''Typhoon Treasure''''' is a 1938 Australian adventure film directed by [[Noel Monkman]] and starring [[Campbell Copelin]], [[Gwen Munro]], and [[Joe Valli]]. It is set in [[New Guinea]] although shot on the [[Great Barrier Reef]] and the [[Queensland]] coast. It was Monkman's first dramatic feature film after several years making documentaries.\n\n==Premise==\nAlan Richards is the sole survivor of a pearling lugger which has been shipwrecked on [[Pakema Reef]] during a typhoon. He sets out to recover some pearls which went missing in the wreck, crossing through the jungle and fighting headhunters.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Campbell Copelin]] as Alan Richards\n*[[Gwen Munro]] as Jean Roberts\n*[[Joe Valli]] as Scotty McLeod\n*Douglas Herald as Buck Thompson\n*[[Kenneth Brampton]] as Alfred Webb\n*Norman French as patrol officer\n*Utan Walters as Utan\n*[[Marshall Crosby]]\n*Moncrieff Macallum\n*Ossie Wenban\n*Douglas Channell\n*Benjamin Brown\n\n==Production==\nIn the mid 1930s, Noel Monkman was working with [[F. W. Thring]] making documentaries. Thring offered to back Monkman in making a dramatic feature, and provided him with a writer, [[John P. McLeod]]. Thring planned to make the movie after visiting Hollywood in 1936<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11037845 |title=Entertainments GOOD VAUDEVILLE. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=28 May 1936 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> but died that year.\n\n[[Cinesound Productions]] offered to buy the script but Monkman elected to make it himself. He formed a syndicate with Bruce Cummings and Commonwealth Laboratories, who provided the crew.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27987813 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILM. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 May 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41809965 |title=\"TYPHOON TREASURE.\". |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=25 June 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFilming commenced June 1937. The film was shot mostly on location in North Queensland, on the [[Great Barrier Reef]], the Yorke Peninsula and [[Torres Strait]]. [[Joe Valli]] started filming in June but [[Gwen Munro]] did not arrive until October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41820134 |title=TALKIE STAR ARRIVES. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=6 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41817632 |title=JOE VALLI IS BACK. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=26 June 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter the location work was completed, some studio scenes were filmed at Commonwealth Film Laboratories' studio at the [[Sydney Showground (Moore Park)|Sydney Showground]].<ref name=\"pike\"/>\n\nMusic was collated from popular classics including [[Tchaikovsky]]'s ''Swan Lake''.\n\n===Death of crew member===\nWhile filming underwater scenes on [[Green Island (Queensland)|Green Island]] in October, one of the divers, James Bell, died of [[myocarditis]]. Bruce Cummings, who was in charge of underwater photography, went down in a diving cylinder, followed a few minutes later by Bell, who was his assistant. A few minutes later Cummings noticed something was wrong with Bell. When they brought him to the surface he was dead.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36383001 |title=DIVER DEAD WHEN BROUGHT UP. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=29 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=30 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41823852 |title=DEATH OF DIVER. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=28 October 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> An inquest was later held which found no negligence.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41833452 |title=DIVER'S COLLAPSE. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=24 December 1937 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41835171 |title=Death of Film Diver. |newspaper=[[The Cairns Post]] |location=Qld. |date=5 January 1938 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nReviews generally found the story formulaic but enjoyed the direction and settings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17533043 |title=FILM REVIEWS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=31 October 1938 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIt was sold to America<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17614362 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILM FOR AMERICAN RELEASE. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=15 June 1939 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and a shortened version of the film screened in England in 1943. In the 1950s rights to the film were bought by George Maclolm who cut it down to 40 minutes and reissued it as ''The Perils of Pakema Reef''.<ref name=\"pike\">Andrew Pike and Ross Cooper, Australian Film 1900\u20131977: A Guide to Feature Film Production, Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1998, 182.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0032069|title=Typhoon Treasure}}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=typhoon%20treasure;querytype=;rec=3;resCount=10 ''Typhoon Treasure''] at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n*[http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/typhoon-treasure ''Typhoon Treasure''] at Oz Movies\n\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure films]]\n[[Category:Australian adventure films]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePremise:add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typhoon_Treasure"}
{"title_page": "Liu Shaozi", "text_new": "'''Liu Shaozi''' (\u7559\u7d39\u93a1) was a nephew of [[Liu Congxiao]], a warlord late in the [[History of China|Chinese]] [[Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms Period]].  Under some traditional accounts, he briefly controlled [[Qingyuan Jiedushi|Qingyuan Circuit]] (headquartered in modern [[Quanzhou]], [[Fujian]]) after his uncle Liu Congxiao's death before being overthrown by the officers [[Chen Hongjin]] and [[Zhang Hansi]].\n\nLiu Congxiao had controlled Qingyuan as its military governor (''[[Jiedushi]]'') ever since then late 940s.  As he was sonless, he adopted both Liu Shaozi and Liu Shaozi's older brother Liu Shaoji (\u7559\u7d39\u9324) as his sons.  (Both Liu Shaoji and Liu Shaozi were biological sons of Liu Congxiao's older brother Liu Congyuan (\u7559\u5f9e\u9858).)<ref name=HS483>''[[History of Song]]'', [[:zh:s:\u5b8b\u53f2/\u5377483|vol. 483]].</ref>  Liu Congxiao apparently died in 962, while being vassals of both [[Southern Tang]] and [[Song dynasty|Song]].  Under the account given in the ''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'' (also adopted in the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals of the Ten Kingdoms]]''), after Liu Congxiao's death, as Liu Shaoji was then on a tributary mission sent by Liu Congxiao to the Southern Tang court, Liu Shaozi took over as acting military governor.  However, not long after, Chen seized him and falsely accused him of planning to submit to [[Wuyue]], and then delivered him to Southern Tang and supported Zhang as the new acting military governor.<ref name=XZZTJ2>''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'', [[:zh:s:\u7e8c\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377002|vol. 2]].</ref>  Under the account in the ''[[History of Song]]'', the coup happened before Liu Congxiao's death, and therefore (implicitly) Liu Shaozi never controlled the circuit\u2014but under Chen's biography, it gave the same account as the ''Xu Zizhi Tongjian'' (i.e., the coup was during Liu Shaozi's rule).<ref name=HS483/>  What Liu Shaozi's fate was after being delivered to Southern Tang was not recorded in history.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n<references/>\n* ''[[History of Song]]'', [[:zh:s:\u5b8b\u53f2/\u5377483|vol. 483]].\n* ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals of the Ten Kingdoms]]'', [https://archive.org/stream/06080963.cn#page/n64/mode/2up vol. 93].\n* ''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'', [[:zh:s:\u7e8c\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377002|vol. 2]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\n{{s-bef|before=[[Liu Congxiao]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Ruler of China (Southern Fujian) (''de facto'')|years=962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zhang Hansi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Shaozi}}\n[[Category:10th-century births]]\n[[Category:Hokkien people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Quanzhou]]\n[[Category:Generals from Fujian]]\n[[Category:Southern Tang politicians]]\n[[Category:Southern Tang generals]]\n[[Category:Song dynasty politicians from Fujian]]\n[[Category:Song dynasty generals]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "text_old": "'''LIu Shaozi''' (\u7559\u7d39\u93a1) was a nephew of [[Liu Congxiao]], a warlord late in the [[History of China|Chinese]] [[Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms Period]].  Under some traditional accounts, he briefly controlled [[Qingyuan Jiedushi|Qingyuan Circuit]] (headquartered in modern [[Quanzhou]], [[Fujian]]) after his uncle Liu Congxiao's death before being overthrown by the officers [[Chen Hongjin]] and [[Zhang Hansi]].\n\nLiu Congxiao had controlled Qingyuan as its military governor (''[[Jiedushi]]'') ever since then late 940s.  As he was sonless, he adopted both Liu Shaozi and Liu Shaozi's older brother Liu Shaoji (\u7559\u7d39\u9324) as his sons.  (Both Liu Shaoji and Liu Shaozi were biological sons of Liu Congxiao's older brother Liu Congyuan (\u7559\u5f9e\u9858).)<ref name=HS483>''[[History of Song]]'', [[:zh:s:\u5b8b\u53f2/\u5377483|vol. 483]].</ref>  Liu Congxiao apparently died in 962, while being vassals of both [[Southern Tang]] and [[Song dynasty|Song]].  Under the account given in the ''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'' (also adopted in the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals of the Ten Kingdoms]]''), after Liu Congxiao's death, as Liu Shaoji was then on a tributary mission sent by Liu Congxiao to the Southern Tang court, Liu Shaozi took over as acting military governor.  However, not long after, Chen seized him and falsely accused him of planning to submit to [[Wuyue]], and then delivered him to Southern Tang and supported Zhang as the new acting military governor.<ref name=XZZTJ2>''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'', [[:zh:s:\u7e8c\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377002|vol. 2]].</ref>  Under the account in the ''[[History of Song]]'', the coup happened before Liu Congxiao's death, and therefore (implicitly) Liu Shaozi never controlled the circuit\u2014but under Chen's biography, it gave the same account as the ''Xu Zizhi Tongjian'' (i.e., the coup was during Liu Shaozi's rule).<ref name=HS483/>  What Liu Shaozi's fate was after being delivered to Southern Tang was not recorded in history.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n<references/>\n* ''[[History of Song]]'', [[:zh:s:\u5b8b\u53f2/\u5377483|vol. 483]].\n* ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals of the Ten Kingdoms]]'', [https://archive.org/stream/06080963.cn#page/n64/mode/2up vol. 93].\n* ''[[Xu Zizhi Tongjian]]'', [[:zh:s:\u7e8c\u8cc7\u6cbb\u901a\u9451/\u5377002|vol. 2]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\n{{s-bef|before=[[Liu Congxiao]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Ruler of China (Southern Fujian) (''de facto'')|years=962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zhang Hansi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Shaozi}}\n[[Category:10th-century births]]\n[[Category:Hokkien people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Quanzhou]]\n[[Category:Generals from Fujian]]\n[[Category:Southern Tang politicians]]\n[[Category:Southern Tang generals]]\n[[Category:Song dynasty politicians from Fujian]]\n[[Category:Song dynasty generals]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Prisencolin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liu_Shaozi"}
{"title_page": "Olea europaea subsp. cuspidata", "text_new": "{{Infraspeciesbox\n|image = Olea europaea ssp cuspidata Bra38.png\n|genus = Olea\n|species = europaea\n|subspecies = cuspidata\n|authority = ([[Nathaniel Wallich|Wall.]] & [[George Don|G.Don]]) [[Raffaele Ciferri|Cif.]]<ref name=WCSP>{{WCSP | 355603 | accessdate = 10 August 2017}}</ref>\n|synonyms =\n*''Linociera lebrunii'' <small>Staner</small>\n*''Olea africana'' <small>Mill.</small>\n*''Olea aucheri'' <small>A.Chev. ex Ehrend.</small>\n*''Olea chrysophylla'' <small>Lam.</small>\n*''Olea cuspidata'' <small>Wall. ex G.Don</small>\n*''Olea indica'' <small>Kleinhof ex Burm.f.</small>\n*''Olea kilimandscharica'' <small>Knobl.</small>\n*''Olea monticola'' <small>Gand.</small>\n*''Olea schimperi'' <small>Gand.</small>\n*''Olea somaliensis'' <small>Baker</small>\n*''Olea subtrinervata'' <small>Chiov.</small>\n*''Olea verrucosa'' <small>(Willd.) Link</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=WCSP/>\n}}\n\n'''''Olea europaea'' subsp. ''cuspidata''''' is a subspecies of olive previously described as ''Olea cuspidata'' and ''Olea africana''. It has various [[common name]]s, including '''wild olive''', '''brown olive''', '''Indian olive''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> '''Olienhout'''{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} and '''iron tree'''.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Description==\nThis much-branched evergreen tree varies in size from {{convert|2|to|15|m|ft|sigfig=1}} high.  The leaves have an opposite, decussate arrangement, and are entire, {{convert|3|to|7|cm}} long and {{convert|8|to|25|mm||sigfig=1}} wide; the apex is acute with a small hook or point, and the base is attenuate to cuneate.  Leaf margins are entire and recurved, the upper surface is grey-green and glossy, and the lower surface has a dense covering of silvery, golden or brown scales. Domatia are absent; venation is obvious on the upper surface and obscure on the lower surface; the petiole is up to {{convert|10|mm|1}} long.\n\nFruit are borne in panicles or racemes {{convert|50|to|60|mm}} long. The calyx is four-lobed, about {{convert|1|mm|2}} long. The corolla is greenish-white or cream; the tube is {{convert|1|to|2|mm}} long; lobes are about {{convert|3|mm}} long and reflexed at the anthesis. The two stamens are fused near the top of the corolla tube, with bilobed stigma.\n\nThe globose to ellipsoid fruit is a drupe, {{convert|6|mm}} in diameter and {{convert|15|to|25|mm}} long; it is fleshy, glaucous to a dull shine when ripe, and purple-black. The tree usually flowers in spring.\n\nThe wood is much-prized and durable, with a strong smell similar to [[bay rum]], and is used for fine furniture and [[turnery]].\n\n==Distribution==\nAn extensive native range from South Africa, through Africa, the Middle East, Pakistan, India to China. Subtropical dry forests of ''Olea europaea cuspidata'' are found in the [[Himalayan subtropical broadleaf forests]] [[terrestrial ecoregion|ecoregion]]. In areas where it is not native, such as Australia, it is classified as an environmental weed spread mainly by birds eating the fruit.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Olea europaea subsp. cuspidata|''Olea europaea'' subsp. ''cuspidata''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2671594}}\n\n[[Category:Olea|europaea subsp. cuspidata]]\n[[Category:Plant subspecies]]\n[[Category:Trees of Africa]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Arabian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Trees of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Trees of China]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Indian subcontinent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infraspeciesbox\n|image = Olea europaea ssp cuspidata Bra38.png\n|genus = Olea\n|species = europaea\n|subspecies = cuspidata\n|authority = ([[Nathaniel Wallich|Wall.]] & [[George Don|G.Don]]) [[Raffaele Ciferri|Cif.]]<ref name=WCSP>{{WCSP | 355603 | accessdate = 10 August 2017}}</ref>\n|synonyms =\n*''Linociera lebrunii'' <small>Staner</small>\n*''Olea africana'' <small>Mill.</small>\n*''Olea aucheri'' <small>A.Chev. ex Ehrend.</small>\n*''Olea chrysophylla'' <small>Lam.</small>\n*''Olea cuspidata'' <small>Wall. ex G.Don</small>\n*''Olea indica'' <small>Kleinhof ex Burm.f.</small>\n*''Olea kilimandscharica'' <small>Knobl.</small>\n*''Olea monticola'' <small>Gand.</small>\n*''Olea schimperi'' <small>Gand.</small>\n*''Olea somaliensis'' <small>Baker</small>\n*''Olea subtrinervata'' <small>Chiov.</small>\n*''Olea verrucosa'' <small>(Willd.) Link</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=WCSP/>\n}}\n\n'''''Olea europaea'' subsp. ''cuspidata''''' is a subspecies of olive previously described as ''Olea cuspidata'' and ''Olea africana''. It has various [[common name]]s, including '''wild olive''', '''brown olive''', '''Indian olive''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> '''Olienhout'''{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} and '''iron tree'''.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Description==\nThis much-branched evergreen tree varies in size from {{convert|2|to|15|m|ft|sigfig=1}} high.  The leaves have an opposite, decussate arrangement, and are entire, {{convert|3|to|7|cm}} long and {{convert|8|to|25|mm||sigfig=1}} wide; the apex is acute with a small hook or point, and the base is attenuate to cuneate.  Leaf margins are entire and recurved, the upper surface is grey-green and glossy, and the lower surface has a dense covering of silvery, golden or brown scales. Domatia are absent; venation is obvious on the upper surface and obscure on the lower surface; the petiole is up to {{convert|10|mm|1}} long.\n\nFruit are borne in panicles or racemes {{convert|50|to|60|mm}} long. The calyx is four-lobed, about {{convert|1|mm|2}} long. The corolla is greenish-white or cream; the tube is {{convert|1|to|2|mm}} long; lobes are about {{convert|3|mm}} long and reflexed at the anthesis. The two stamens are fused near the top of the corolla tube, with bilobed stigma.\n\nThe globose to ellipsoid fruit is a drupe, {{convert|6|mm}} in diameter and {{convert|15|to|25|mm}} long; it is fleshy, glaucous to a dull shine when ripe, and purple-black. The tree usually flowers in spring.\n\nThe wood is much-prized and durable, with a strong smell similar to [[bay rum]], and is used for fine furniture and [[turnery]].\n\n==Distribution==\nAn extensive native range from South Africa, through Africa, the Middle East, Pakistan, India to China. Subtropical dry forests of ''Olea europaea cuspidata'' are found in the [[Himalayan subtropical broadleaf forests]] [[terrestrial ecoregion|ecoregion]]. In areas where it is not native, such as Australia, it is classified as a noxious weed.  It is spread mainly by birds eating the fruit.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Olea europaea subsp. cuspidata|''Olea europaea'' subsp. ''cuspidata''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2671594}}\n\n[[Category:Olea|europaea subsp. cuspidata]]\n[[Category:Plant subspecies]]\n[[Category:Trees of Africa]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Arabian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Trees of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Trees of China]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Indian subcontinent]]\n", "name_user": "Akeensurfer2004", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution:The term \"noxious weed\" requires a stricter definition, 'environmental weed' may be more appropriate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olea_europaea_subsp._cuspidata"}
{"title_page": "Purple-crested turaco", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Purple-crested turaco\n| image = Purple-crested Turaco (Gallirex porphyreolophus) (32424422866).jpg\n| image_caption = Nominate race in [[Ithala Game Reserve|Ithala G. R.]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22688380/0 |title=''Gallirex porphyreolophus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Tauraco\n| species = porphyreolophus\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]], 1831)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''purple-crested turaco''' (''Tauraco porphyreolophus'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Musophagidae]]. It is the National Bird of the Kingdom of [[Swaziland]], and the crimson flight feathers of this and related turaco species are important in the ceremonial regalia of the [[House of Dlamini|Swazi royal family]].\n\n==Description==\nThis bird has a purple coloured crest above a green head, a red ring around their eyes, and a black bill. The neck and chest are green and brown. The rest of the body is purple, with red flight feathers.\n\n==Habitat==\nThey live in moist woodland and evergreen forests. They eat mainly fruit.\n\n==Range==\nIt is found in [[Burundi]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Rwanda]], [[South Africa]], [[Swaziland]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. Their southernmost occurrence is at the [[Mtamvuna River]] on the [[KwaZulu-Natal]]-[[Eastern Cape]] border.<ref name=pac>{{cite journal|last=Clancey|first=P. A.|title=A One-time Mecca for Ornithologists |journal=Natalia |date= December 1975 |volume=5 |pages=29\u201335 |url= http://www.natalia.org.za/Files/5/Natalia%20v05%20article%20p29-35%20C.pdf|accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\" >\nFile:Purple-crested turaco, Tauraco porphyreolophus, at uMkhuze Game Reserve, kwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (15413446536).jpg|<center>Close-up of front and head plumage</center>\nFile:Purple-crested turaco, Tauraco porphyreolophus, at uMkhuze Game Reserve, kwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (15433321841).jpg|<center>Visiting a waterhole in [[uMkhuze Game Reserve|uMkhuze G. R.]]</center>\nImage:Tauraco porphyreolophus 1838.jpg|Illustration by [[Andrew Smith (zoologist)|Andrew Smith]], showing crimson primaries\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* National Aviary. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100227122243/http://www.aviary.org/~aviary/bird/meet_common.php?bird=250 Purple-Crested Turaco].\n* International Turaco Society ITS Magazine 1993-2012\n(Swazi References - Spring 2012 Clive Humphreys)\n\n{{Turacos}}\n\n==External links==\n* Purple-crested turaco - [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/371.pdf Species text in The Atlas of Southern African Birds].\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1063701}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:turaco, purple-crested}}\n[[Category:Tauraco|purple-crested turaco]]\n[[Category:Birds of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1831|purple-crested turaco]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Purple-crested turaco\n| image = Purple-crested Turaco (Gallirex porphyreolophus) (32424422866).jpg\n| image_caption = Nominate race in [[Ithala Game Reserve|Ithala G. R.]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22688380/0 |title=''Gallirex porphyreolophus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Tauraco\n| species = porphyreolophus\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]], 1831)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''purple-crested turaco''' (''Tauraco porphyreolophus'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Musophagidae]] family. It is the National Bird of the Kingdom of [[Swaziland]], and the crimson flight feathers of this and related turaco species are important in the ceremonial regalia of the [[House of Dlamini|Swazi royal family]].\n\n==Description==\nThis bird has a purple coloured crest above a green head, a red ring around their eyes, and a black bill. The neck and chest are green and brown. The rest of the body is purple, with red flight feathers.\n\n==Habitat==\nThey live in moist woodland and evergreen forests. They eat mainly fruit.\n\n==Range==\nIt is found in [[Burundi]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Rwanda]], [[South Africa]], [[Swaziland]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. Their southernmost occurrence is at the [[Mtamvuna River]] on the [[KwaZulu-Natal]]-[[Eastern Cape]] border.<ref name=pac>{{cite journal|last=Clancey|first=P. A.|title=A One-time Mecca for Ornithologists |journal=Natalia |date= December 1975 |volume=5 |pages=29\u201335 |url= http://www.natalia.org.za/Files/5/Natalia%20v05%20article%20p29-35%20C.pdf|accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\" >\nFile:Purple-crested turaco, Tauraco porphyreolophus, at uMkhuze Game Reserve, kwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (15413446536).jpg|<center>Close-up of front and head plumage</center>\nFile:Purple-crested turaco, Tauraco porphyreolophus, at uMkhuze Game Reserve, kwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (15433321841).jpg|<center>Visiting a waterhole in [[uMkhuze Game Reserve|uMkhuze G. R.]]</center>\nImage:Tauraco porphyreolophus 1838.jpg|Illustration by [[Andrew Smith (zoologist)|Andrew Smith]], showing crimson primaries\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* National Aviary. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100227122243/http://www.aviary.org/~aviary/bird/meet_common.php?bird=250 Purple-Crested Turaco].\n* International Turaco Society ITS Magazine 1993-2012\n(Swazi References - Spring 2012 Clive Humphreys)\n\n{{Turacos}}\n\n==External links==\n* Purple-